ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Trichomoniasis in Cooper's hawks from Arizona was described by Boal et al
. (1998) in J Wild Diseases 34(3):590-3. They demonstrated that prevalence
of _T. gallinae_ was significantly greater among urban nestlings (85
percent) than among ex-urban nestlings (9 percent), and postulated that the
patterns found were probably caused by 3 factors: doves are hosts for the
parasite, they are present in large numbers in Tucson, and they are the
primary prey of urban Cooper's hawks there. There is no risk of the
infection spreading to humans. - Mod.AS/EP]
